  NDSolve[{y'[x] == y[x], y[0] == 1}, y, {x, 0, 2},
    StepMonitor :&gt; Sow[x]]];
adaptiveFig = ListLinePlot[Differences[stepPositions],
  Frame -&gt; True, FrameLabel -&gt; {"Step index", "Step size h"},
  PlotLabel -&gt; Style[
    "Adaptive step sizes used by NDSolve on y' = y", 12]];
Export["09_RK5_And_Beyond/adaptive-steps.pdf", adaptiveFig];
Export["09_RK5_And_Beyond/adaptive-steps.svg", adaptiveFig];




Adaptive step sizes chosen by NDSolve.



ndSolResult = y[2] /. First[
  NDSolve[{y'[x] == y[x], y[0] == 1}, y, {x, 0, 2}]];
rk4FixedResult = Last[methodRun[rk4Step, f, x0, y0, xEnd, 0.1]][[2]];
{"NDSolve error" -&gt; Abs[ndSolResult - Exp[2]],
 "RK4 fixed h=0.1 error" -&gt; Abs[rk4FixedResult - Exp[2]]}




NDSolve defaults to the Dormand-Prince method (DOPRI5): a 7-stage explicit Runge-Kutta scheme that simultaneously computes 4th-order and 5th-order estimates from the same \(k\) values. The difference between the two estimates is a cheap error indicator. When the indicator exceeds the tolerance, the step is rejected and repeated with smaller \(h\). When it falls below the tolerance, the next step uses larger \(h\). The net effect is that evaluations concentrate where the solution changes rapidly and steps stretch where it is flat.

9.10 Stiff Equations: Where All Explicit RK Methods Fail
Stiffness is a different breakdown. A stiff ODE has components that decay at very different rates: one component decays slowly (the solution of interest) and another decays extremely rapidly (a fast transient). Explicit RK methods are conditionally stable: they require \(h \cdot |\lambda|\) to stay within a bounded region. For a stiff problem, the fast eigenvalue forces \(h\) to be tiny even when the interesting part of the solution changes slowly.

fStiff[x_, y_] := -1000*y
exactStiff[x_] := Exp[-1000*x]
{"Stability bound on h" -&gt; 2.785/1000,
 "h=0.002 (h*lambda=-2)" -&gt; "inside stability region",
 "h=0.005 (h*lambda=-5)" -&gt; "outside stability region"}





runStable   = methodRun[rk4Step, fStiff, 0, 1.0, 0.02, 0.002];
runUnstable = methodRun[rk4Step, fStiff, 0, 1.0, 0.02, 0.005];
exactPts = Table[{x, exactStiff[x]}, {x, 0, 0.02, 0.001}];
stiffFig = ListLinePlot[
  {runStable, runUnstable, exactPts},
  PlotLegends -&gt; {"RK4 h=0.002 (stable)",
                  "RK4 h=0.005 (unstable)", "Exact"},
  PlotLabel -&gt; Style[
    "Stiff equation y' = -1000 y: stable vs. unstable step", 11],
  Frame -&gt; True, FrameLabel -&gt; {"x", "y"},
  PlotRange -&gt; All];
Export["09_RK5_And_Beyond/stiff.pdf", stiffFig];
Export["09_RK5_And_Beyond/stiff.svg", stiffFig];




Explicit RK4 with \(h\) outside the stability region oscillates and grows.



stiffSol = NDSolve[
  {y'[x] == -1000*y[x], y[0] == 1}, y, {x, 0, 0.02}];
{"NDSolve at x=0.02" -&gt; y[0.02] /. stiffSol[[1]],
 "Exact at x=0.02" -&gt; exactStiff[0.02],
 "Error" -&gt; Abs[(y[0.02] /. stiffSol[[1]]) - exactStiff[0.02]]}




The explicit RK4 at \(h = 0.005\) shows oscillations that grow without bound: \(h \cdot |\lambda| = 5\) lies outside the stability region, and each step amplifies rather than damps the error. The stable \(h = 0.002\) follows the exact solution. NDSolve detects the stiffness and automatically switches to an implicit solver — by default a singly-diagonally implicit Runge-Kutta method (SDIRK) whose stability region covers the entire left half of the complex plane, eliminating the step-size constraint.
